      <header class="waa-header">
        <h1 class="waa-title">What is Art Analysis?</h1>
        <p class="waa-subtitle">What art analysis actually does — and what Art Lab does differently</p>
      </header>

      <div class="waa-body">

        <p>Here's something worth knowing before you read the comparison: there's no neutral starting point in art analysis. Every framework makes a choice. What to look at first. What counts as evidence. Whether someone gets to decide if the work is good. Those aren't technical decisions — they're philosophical ones. And the frameworks disagree with each other more than they'd like to admit.</p>

        <p>Feldman came first, at least in the American classroom. He was a professor at the University of Georgia, and in 1970 he published a method that's still the dominant model in K–12 and undergraduate art education: describe, analyze, interpret, judge. Four steps, in order. The logic is sound — you shouldn't arrive at a verdict before you've looked. But step four asks you to decide whether the work succeeds or fails. That's not a neutral move. It positions the viewer as the authority and the work as the defendant.</p>

        <p>Panofsky was working from a different problem. He was an art historian, and his question was: how do you recover what an image <em>meant</em> to the people who made it? His three-level method — what you see, what it symbolizes, what it reveals about its cultural moment — is genuinely powerful for Renaissance altarpieces. Less so for a painting made last Tuesday. The method requires cultural and historical knowledge to function. Which means it locks out people who don't have that knowledge. And it builds in an assumption that meaning is something you retrieve from history, not something happening right now in front of you.</p>

        <p>VTS — Visual Thinking Strategies — came out of a different tradition entirely. It was developed in the 1990s at the Museum of Modern Art, by cognitive psychologist Abigail Housen and educator Philip Yenawine. Their insight was simple and underestimated: traditional art education doesn't work for beginners. What works is looking carefully, saying what you see, and being asked for your evidence. The three VTS questions do that. They don't require expertise. They produce real engagement. And they deliberately withhold judgment — all responses are treated as equally valid. That's a pedagogical choice, not an analytical limitation. But it also means VTS produces discussion, not analysis. There's no document, no framework, no vocabulary for mechanisms.</p>

        <p>And here's where Art Lab sits differently from all three.</p>

        <p>Feldman, Panofsky, and VTS are all, in different ways, frameworks for <em>meaning-making</em>. They move toward interpretation. Toward what the work says, represents, or communicates. Art Lab moves in the opposite direction. It starts with what your visual system is doing in the first fraction of a second — before meaning, before interpretation, before the viewer decides whether they're the type of person who "gets" art.</p>

        <p>That's not a philosophical preference. It's a structural commitment. The RAP Protocol requires at least two independent visual observations before any interpretive claim is permitted. The three language registers — observable, perceptual effect, interpretive — are kept formally separate by anchoring phrases. And evaluation is prohibited by design. Not de-emphasized. Prohibited. The words <em>good, bad, successful, effective</em> don't appear in an Art Lab analysis because the framework refuses the role of judge.</p>

        <p>What this makes possible is something the other frameworks can't quite do: a full analysis of abstract, non-representational, or contemporary work that requires no cultural competency to begin. You don't need to know the iconography. You don't need art history. You need to look at what's physically present and name what it does to your nervous system before you assign it meaning.</p>

        <p>That's a real difference. The question is whether it's a better difference or just a different one — and that's worth being honest about. Art Lab's 54 principles are drawn from neuroaesthetics and perceptual psychology, but their application to specific images is AI-mediated, not experimentally confirmed. The eval loop under development is designed to test whether outputs score well on four criteria. That's rigorous thinking. It's not yet evidence.</p>

        <p>Feldman gets students to look. Panofsky gets scholars to recover cultural meaning. VTS gets museum visitors to talk. Art Lab gets working artists to see what's operating in their own work before they decide what it means.</p>

        <p>Those are different jobs. The grid shows you how differently each framework is built to do them.</p>

      </div>

      <!-- Comparison Grid -->
      <div class="waa-grid-wrap">
        <header class="waa-grid-header">
          <h2 class="waa-grid-title">Art analysis frameworks — comparison grid</h2>
          <p class="waa-grid-subtitle">Four models across nine dimensions. Art Lab is the rightmost column.</p>
        </header>

        <div class="waa-table-scroll">
          <table class="waa-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th></th>
                <th><span class="waa-col-label">Feldman</span><span class="waa-col-year">1970 · art education</span></th>
                <th><span class="waa-col-label">Panofsky</span><span class="waa-col-year">1939 · art history</span></th>
                <th><span class="waa-col-label">VTS</span><span class="waa-col-year">1990s · museum education</span></th>
                <th class="waa-col-artlab"><span class="waa-col-label">Art Lab</span><span class="waa-col-year">Art Lab framework</span></th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>

              <tr class="waa-divider"><td colspan="5">Structure</td></tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Primary purpose</td>
                <td>Teach students to critique systematically</td>
                <td>Recover meaning from historical images</td>
                <td>Build visual literacy through group discussion</td>
                <td>Map perceptual mechanisms operating in the work</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Steps / sequence</td>
                <td>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--blue">1 Describe</span>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--blue">2 Analyze</span>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--blue">3 Interpret</span>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--blue">4 Judge</span>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--teal">1 Pre-iconographic</span>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--teal">2 Iconographic</span>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--teal">3 Iconological</span>
                </td>
                <td>3 facilitated questions, looped. No fixed endpoint.</td>
                <td>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--purple">Observable</span>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--purple">Perceptual effect</span>
                  <span class="waa-pill waa-pill--purple">Interpretive claim</span>
                  — kept formally separate, never merged
                </td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Output type</td>
                <td>Written or oral critique</td>
                <td>Scholarly interpretation</td>
                <td>Facilitated group discussion; no document</td>
                <td>Structured written analysis anchored to visual evidence</td>
              </tr>

              <tr class="waa-divider"><td colspan="5">Evidence and language</td></tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Observation-first requirement</td>
                <td><span class="waa-partial">Partial</span> — steps 1–2 are nominally objective, but no formal gate prevents early interpretation</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes</span> — level 1 must precede levels 2 and 3</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes</span> — "What do you see that makes you say that?" enforces evidence before inference</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Structural</span> — RAP Protocol: no interpretation without at least two independent visual observations</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Language registers distinguished</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — objective and subjective phases alternate but share vocabulary</td>
                <td><span class="waa-partial">Partially</span> — three levels are conceptually distinct but use overlapping language</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — open-ended questions don't enforce language type</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes, formally</span> — three anchoring phrases prevent register collapse</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Perceptual / neural mechanisms named</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — uses elements and principles of design</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — operates on iconographic and cultural categories</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — deliberately avoids expert vocabulary</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes</span> — 54 principles and 11 Roots drawn from neuroaesthetics and perceptual psychology</td>
              </tr>

              <tr class="waa-divider"><td colspan="5">Evaluation and intent</td></tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Includes evaluation / judgment</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes, required</span> — step 4 asks explicitly whether the work "succeeds or fails"</td>
                <td><span class="waa-partial">Implicitly</span> — iconological reading carries evaluative weight</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — all interpretations treated as equally valid</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">Structurally prohibited</span> — evaluative words are banned by design</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Artist intent addressed</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes</span> — interpretation step asks "what is the artist trying to communicate?"</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes</span> — iconological level recovers the worldview of the artist</td>
                <td><span class="waa-partial">Sometimes</span> — intent may arise but is not required</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">Prohibited</span> — no claims about what the work "tries" to do</td>
              </tr>

              <tr class="waa-divider"><td colspan="5">Scope and access</td></tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Cultural / historical knowledge required</td>
                <td><span class="waa-partial">Some</span> — works best with representational art</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes, substantially</span> — levels 2 and 3 require iconographic competency</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — designed for naive viewers</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">No</span> — full analysis runs from perceptual observation alone</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Works on abstract / non-objective art</td>
                <td><span class="waa-partial">Partially</span> — interpretation and judgment become difficult without subject matter</td>
                <td><span class="waa-no">Poorly</span> — built for representational, historically-situated images</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes</span> — open-ended questions apply to any image</td>
                <td><span class="waa-yes">Yes</span> — perceptual mechanisms operate regardless of subject matter</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Primary audience</td>
                <td>Students; art educators</td>
                <td>Art historians; scholars</td>
                <td>Museum visitors; K–12 students</td>
                <td>Working artists; art-curious; educators</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td>Designed for solo or group use</td>
                <td>Both</td>
                <td>Solo (scholarly)</td>
                <td>Group — the discussion IS the method</td>
                <td>Solo — interrogation window allows dialogue</td>
              </tr>

            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p class="waa-footnote">Sources: Feldman (1970), Panofsky (1939/1972), Housen &amp; Yenawine / VTS (1990s–present), Art Lab framework.</p>
      </div>

    </article>
  </div>
